Beijing (CNN) -- The trial of Bo Xilai, a former darling of the all-powerful Communist Party, will begin Thursday, China's state-run Xinhua news agency said.

Authorities claim Bo abused his official state position to seek financial benefits, resulting in "huge losses to the nation and the people."

He is charged with bribery, embezzlement and abuse of power, the Jinan Intermediate People's Court said Sunday.

A source close to the Bo family for decades said this month the claims are "ridiculous."

"The charges go way back when Bo was in Dalian," the source said. "That's more than 20 years ago. So they cannot find anything more recent?"

The trial begins another chapter in a gripping tale of murder, betrayal and political factionalism. It caps the biggest political scandal to hit China in decades.

